s an e-folding lifetime of more than one year. For each mode, the rms velocity at the equator is in the range of 1–3 m s{\textless}sup{\textgreater}−1{\textless}sup/{\textgreater}, with the largest values for {\textless}i{\textgreater}m{\textless}i/{\textgreater} ∼ 10. No evidence for the {\textless}i{\textgreater}m{\textless}i/{\textgreater} = 2 sectoral mode is found in the power spectrum, implying that the rms velocity of this mode is below ∼0.5 m s{\textless}sup{\textgreater}−1{\textless}sup/{\textgreater}.{\textless}i{\textgreater}Conclusions{\textless}i/{\textgreater}. This work confirms the existence of equatorial global Rossby waves in the solar interior over the past two solar cycles and shows that time-distance helioseismology is a promising technique to study them deep in the convection zone.},
