r} Sectoral {\textless}i{\textgreater}r{\textless}i/{\textgreater} modes with azimuthal orders {\textless}i{\textgreater}m{\textless}i/{\textgreater} = 2 and 3 would produce RV oscillations with amplitudes of 76.4 and 19.6 cm s{\textless}sup{\textgreater}−1{\textless}sup/{\textgreater} and periods of 19.16 and 10.22 days, respectively, for a star with an inclination of the rotation axis to the line of sight {\textless}i{\textgreater}i{\textless}i/{\textgreater} = 60°. Therefore, they may produce rather sharp peaks in the Fourier spectrum of the radial velocity time series that could lead to spurious planetary detections.{\textless}i{\textgreater}Conclusions.{\textless}i/{\textgreater} Sectoral {\textless}i{\textgreater}r{\textless}i/{\textgreater} modes may represent a source of confusion in the case of slowly rotating inactive stars that are preferential targets for RV planet search. The main limitation of the present investigation is the lack of observational constraints on the amplitude of the {\textless}i{\textgreater}m{\textless}i/{\textgreater} = 2 mode on the Sun.},
